1
00:02:13,978 --> 00:02:17,377
The curator agreed to remove
the paintings from the exhibition

2
00:02:17,457 --> 00:02:21,176
and sent a letter to the artist
inviting him to submit alternatives.

3
00:02:21,256 --> 00:02:23,975
Unfortunately,
the offer was refused point-blank.

4
00:02:24,055 --> 00:02:28,574
- He's threatened to go to the press.
- Mr Norman Lindsay, I take it?

5
00:02:28,654 --> 00:02:31,773
- You've heard of him.
- Well, I like to keep abreast.

6
00:02:31,853 --> 00:02:37,651
The last thing we want is a scandal.
Anyway, here they are.

7
00:02:38,770 --> 00:02:40,810
Yes.

8
00:02:45,048 --> 00:02:49,407
A case could be made for the
first three. They're merely vulgar.

9
00:02:49,487 --> 00:02:52,766
But this one
is certainly blasphemous.

10
00:02:52,846 --> 00:02:57,524
- And you want me to talk him round?
- It's on the way to your new parish.

11
00:02:57,604 --> 00:03:01,363
I think an outsider has more of
a chance of getting through to him

12
00:03:01,443 --> 00:03:02,842
than any of us locals.

13
00:03:02,922 --> 00:03:05,801
I gather you were something
of a progressive at Oxford.

14
00:03:05,881 --> 00:03:09,640
Don't believe everything you hear
but yes, element of truth in that.

15
00:03:10,680 --> 00:03:13,679
He's happy to put you
and your wife up for the night.

16
00:03:13,759 --> 00:03:16,998
I think he rather relishes
the idea of a good argument.

17
00:03:17,078 --> 00:03:19,917
Well, if his reputation
is anything to go by,

18
00:03:19,997 --> 00:03:24,475
he'd love to shock the socks off
any churchman that goes near him.

19
00:03:24,555 --> 00:03:28,034
May I introduce you to my wife?
I don't think you've met.

20
00:03:30,993 --> 00:03:34,032
Estella, the Bishop of Sydney.
My wife, Estella.

21
00:03:34,112 --> 00:03:36,112
- Welcome to Australia.
- Thank you.

22
00:04:25,215 --> 00:04:27,495
- Morning.
- Tickets, please.

23
00:04:30,414 --> 00:04:33,973
- Do you know if a taxi's waiting?
- Yeah. There's not.

24
00:04:35,812 --> 00:04:39,491
I, um, understand one was booked
to go to Mr Lindsay's place.

25
00:04:40,251 --> 00:04:42,330
Doing a bit of modelling, are yous?

26
00:04:42,410 --> 00:04:44,249
No, I certainly am not.

27
00:04:45,569 --> 00:04:50,367
Taxi's been a bit late lately.
You'd be better off down at the pub.

28
00:04:50,687 --> 00:04:53,486
May we leave our baggage here?

29
00:04:53,566 --> 00:04:56,285
I'm about to knock off.
It'll be pilfered.

30
00:04:56,365 --> 00:05:00,484
Would you mind giving us
a hand with it, then?

31
00:05:00,564 --> 00:05:03,803
- Oh, I'm awfully sorry.
- I'll forgive you.

32
00:05:03,883 --> 00:05:06,322
- Millions wouldn't.
- Oh, dear.

33
00:05:07,202 --> 00:05:09,361
Try the pub.
It's just down the hill.

34
00:05:38,232 --> 00:05:42,110
- Morning.
- Get fucked. Get fucked.

35
00:05:46,069 --> 00:05:47,748
Ah, fuck.

36
00:05:50,308 --> 00:05:52,227
Aw, fuck.

37
00:05:57,345 --> 00:05:58,905
Watch the language, everyone.

38
00:05:58,985 --> 00:06:03,143
Gents only in the bar.
Ladies' lounge is through the door.

39
00:06:03,223 --> 00:06:07,382
Yes, we don't want a drink.
We just want a taxi, if there is one.

40
00:06:07,462 --> 00:06:10,341
- Reg is at a funeral.
- I see.

41
00:06:10,421 --> 00:06:13,540
- You could be in for a long wait.
- Oh, yes?

42
00:06:13,620 --> 00:06:15,579
It's his funeral.

43
00:06:18,258 --> 00:06:20,978
Well... Thanks.

44
00:06:21,058 --> 00:06:23,177
Hey! I got my eye on you!

45
00:06:24,216 --> 00:06:27,375
- Where yous goin'?
- Out to Mr Lindsay's place.

46
00:06:31,974 --> 00:06:35,413
We're goin' out that way.
We can give you a lift.

47
00:06:35,493 --> 00:06:39,412
- Thank you. Thank you very much.
- After we finish our beers.

48
00:07:10,041 --> 00:07:11,601
Anthony?

49
00:07:19,039 --> 00:07:20,878
They can't wait forever.

50
00:07:36,113 --> 00:07:38,072
Fine. Come on, then.

51
00:08:18,899 --> 00:08:21,338
Thank you.

52
00:08:27,576 --> 00:08:29,935
Thanks for the lift.

53
00:08:30,015 --> 00:08:31,855
I don't mean to be rude but...

54
00:08:31,935 --> 00:08:34,494
you got a bit of food
on the side of your mouth.

55
00:08:35,573 --> 00:08:37,773
Thanks.

56
00:08:40,572 --> 00:08:41,851
See ya later.

57
00:08:47,650 --> 00:08:50,249
Sorry about that, Piglet.
You all right?

58
00:08:51,448 --> 00:08:54,847
They swear an awful lot.
They tend to, types like that.

59
00:08:54,927 --> 00:08:57,646
- They didn't really say anything.
- Good.

60
00:08:57,726 --> 00:09:01,845
- Now, where is everyone?
- Maybe Mr Lindsay changed his mind.

61
00:09:12,561 --> 00:09:15,201
Pooh, look, there's something here.

62
00:09:16,560 --> 00:09:19,919
Dear visitors, sorry we missed you.
Gone out for a picnic.

63
00:09:19,999 --> 00:09:21,958
Make yourselves at home.

64
00:09:24,477 --> 00:09:26,837
Well, I suppose
we'd better not go in.

65
00:09:28,716 --> 00:09:30,635
Let's sit over by the pond.

66
00:10:01,665 --> 00:10:03,665
- Mrs Campion?
- Hello.

67
00:10:09,423 --> 00:10:11,742
What? Ah! Sorry.

68
00:10:13,142 --> 00:10:14,621
I was fast asleep there.

69
00:10:14,701 --> 00:10:19,699
You must be Mr Lindsay.
Lindsay Campion, my wife Norman.

70
00:10:19,779 --> 00:10:22,978
- Estella.
- Just out from England?

71
00:10:23,058 --> 00:10:25,737
That's it. We arrived
just a couple of weeks ago.

72
00:10:25,817 --> 00:10:28,057
So they weren't game to send a local?

73
00:10:28,137 --> 00:10:30,456
Well, you...
you're exactly on our way.

74
00:10:31,536 --> 00:10:35,014
Oh, well. I'm glad
you got here in one piece.

75
00:10:35,094 --> 00:10:37,614
Excuse me, I gotta get back to work.

76
00:10:37,694 --> 00:10:41,652
Giddy and Sheela'll show you a room.
You'd probably like to freshen up.

77
00:10:41,732 --> 00:10:44,571
- We'd love to, thank you.
- Thank you very much.

78
00:10:46,771 --> 00:10:49,490
- You take that for me...
- This way, ladies and gents.

79
00:10:49,570 --> 00:10:50,969
Maggie!

80
00:11:01,686 --> 00:11:04,325
Thank you. Lovely.

81
00:11:05,604 --> 00:11:07,484
You'll have trouble sleeping.

82
00:11:07,564 --> 00:11:10,523
She sleeps next door
and she snores terribly.

83
00:11:11,562 --> 00:11:15,481
- I do not.
- She sounds like two possums mating.

84
00:11:15,561 --> 00:11:18,520
That's so horrible and it's not true.

85
00:11:20,200 --> 00:11:21,999
Whereabouts is the, uh...

86
00:11:22,639 --> 00:11:24,478
Take him out to the thunder box.

87
00:11:25,718 --> 00:11:27,397
Just a tick.

88
00:11:30,396 --> 00:11:32,995
I've never snored in my life.

89
00:11:33,075 --> 00:11:37,074
I think snoring
can be quite charming, actually.

90
00:11:37,474 --> 00:11:39,553
This way.

91
00:11:39,633 --> 00:11:43,712
Why do they call it a thunder box?
Cos it's out in the wind and rain?

92
00:11:43,792 --> 00:11:47,391
I suppose. But you always need
to keep your shoes on.

93
00:11:47,471 --> 00:11:52,509
- Are there stinging nettles?
- Yes, and scorpions and centipedes.

94
00:11:52,589 --> 00:11:53,869
Hell.

95
00:11:53,949 --> 00:11:56,708
- Can you swim?
- Not very well.

96
00:11:58,187 --> 00:12:02,146
I'll wake you up. There's
a swimming hole we go to every day.

97
00:12:02,226 --> 00:12:05,545
- I'm Sheela.
- Estella.

98
00:12:08,344 --> 00:12:11,623
Does he always take the Bible
with him to the dunny?

99
00:12:11,703 --> 00:12:15,542
It wasn't the Bible. He just doesn't
like wasting time, that's all.

100
00:12:18,541 --> 00:12:22,619
Well, from the size of it,
he could be there all night.

101
00:12:24,818 --> 00:12:27,937
I should've warned him
about the redbacks.

102
00:12:28,017 --> 00:12:31,096
- What are they?
- Small spiders with big teeth.

103
00:12:31,176 --> 00:12:35,055
- They live under toilet seats.
- How do you know if they're there?

104
00:12:35,135 --> 00:12:37,094
By the screams.

105
00:13:08,004 --> 00:13:10,324
Ah, there you are.

106
00:13:11,163 --> 00:13:13,243
Mr Lindsay's wonderful, isn't he?

107
00:13:13,323 --> 00:13:15,642
He said we're gonna do
The Sirens next.

108
00:13:15,722 --> 00:13:17,721
- Do you know about them?
- Certainly.

109
00:13:17,801 --> 00:13:21,320
They lived on the island of Atlantis
and sang songs from the cliffs

110
00:13:21,400 --> 00:13:25,279
and sailors from passing ships were
driven mad by these gorgeous voices.

111
00:13:25,359 --> 00:13:28,238
And the ships would be dashed
against the rocks

112
00:13:28,318 --> 00:13:31,157
and the sailors dragged down
to a blissful death

113
00:13:31,237 --> 00:13:35,315
with the voices of the sirens
ringing in their ears.

114
00:13:35,395 --> 00:13:38,474
I think myths
are a bit stupid, really.

115
00:13:39,394 --> 00:13:41,353
I'll be wearing this.

116
00:13:42,673 --> 00:13:44,992
You know, you could pose, too,
if you like.

117
00:13:45,072 --> 00:13:48,511
He always needs more models.
Go on, try it. Please.

118
00:13:48,591 --> 00:13:50,870
There's some male ones too.

119
00:13:50,950 --> 00:13:52,830
I don't think that's quite for us.

120
00:13:52,910 --> 00:13:56,508
Well, you could always wear a dagger,
strategically placed.

121
00:13:59,348 --> 00:14:04,906
Or a sword. Whichever you need.
And dinner's ready.

122
00:14:04,986 --> 00:14:07,105
Oh, that's right.

123
00:14:07,185 --> 00:14:09,184
I was sent to fetch you.

124
00:14:10,904 --> 00:14:15,262
I don't... like people thinking
I'm like the other models.

125
00:14:15,342 --> 00:14:18,901
I'm working here as a maid.
Mr Lindsay asked me to pose

126
00:14:18,981 --> 00:14:22,420
and I said I would
if I could keep my clothes on.

127
00:14:22,500 --> 00:14:26,499
Because I really think it's important
to keep one's mystique,

128
00:14:26,579 --> 00:14:28,898
don't you, Mr Campion?

129
00:14:28,978 --> 00:14:32,017
Is it Mr Campion
or Father Anthony?

130
00:14:32,097 --> 00:14:33,696
It's, uh, it's Tony.

131
00:14:35,536 --> 00:14:39,334
Do you think it's a sin... Tony?

132
00:14:39,414 --> 00:14:42,453
I don't think there's anything sinful
about the body.

133
00:14:42,533 --> 00:14:46,012
There's a tradition of religious
painting featuring the nude.

134
00:14:46,092 --> 00:14:50,851
It's a question of... how the artist
uses the body that's important.

135
00:14:50,931 --> 00:14:55,009
So, do you think
Mr Lindsay's paintings are rude?

136
00:14:59,288 --> 00:15:01,247
Some I think are profane.

137
00:15:02,527 --> 00:15:05,726
Oh, that's good. I'm starving.

138
00:15:05,806 --> 00:15:08,365
I only eat once a day
cos my mother's very fat

139
00:15:08,445 --> 00:15:10,004
and it runs in my family.

140
00:15:10,084 --> 00:15:13,283
You should see my grandpa.
He looks like the Michelin Man.

141
00:15:13,363 --> 00:15:16,602
You know, the one
with all those tyres around him?

142
00:15:16,682 --> 00:15:19,801
He eats like a horse!
He puts tomato sauce on everything.

143
00:15:21,081 --> 00:15:25,439
It was a very enlightened society.
The artists made all the decisions.

144
00:15:25,519 --> 00:15:27,879
That's why there's no record
of warfare

145
00:15:27,959 --> 00:15:30,318
between the Atlanteans
and anyone else.

146
00:15:30,398 --> 00:15:33,037
The main question is, where was it?

147
00:15:33,117 --> 00:15:35,796
The Mediterranean
is the most likely spot.

148
00:15:35,876 --> 00:15:38,275
They're always digging up pottery

149
00:15:38,355 --> 00:15:41,074
that doesn't belong to
any known civilization.

150
00:15:41,154 --> 00:15:43,913
How could a complete people
just disappear?

151
00:15:43,993 --> 00:15:47,872
Well, a cataclysm. They were all
wiped out in a cataclysm.

152
00:15:47,952 --> 00:15:50,031
Whole island sank in an earthquake.

153
00:15:50,111 --> 00:15:52,870
So you're a genuine believer
in Atlantis?

154
00:15:52,950 --> 00:15:56,349
Well, I lived there
in a former incarnation.

155
00:15:58,269 --> 00:16:01,907
I ask because the cataclysm can be
seen as an image of moral collapse

156
00:16:01,987 --> 00:16:05,746
and some think we're going through
a similar period of decay.

157
00:16:05,826 --> 00:16:08,025
Do you explore that in your painting?

158
00:16:08,105 --> 00:16:13,024
I think people have always
been decaying, whenever they can.

159
00:16:13,104 --> 00:16:16,703
He's just a very depraved man,
I'm afraid, Mr Campion.

160
00:16:16,783 --> 00:16:18,382
No one's safe.

161
00:16:22,141 --> 00:16:24,020
I'm bloody bored!

162
00:16:26,739 --> 00:16:28,659
Have you seen those fairies lately?

163
00:16:28,739 --> 00:16:31,818
A couple of them were out
last Friday.

164
00:16:31,898 --> 00:16:33,977
- They were not!
- They were too.

165
00:16:34,057 --> 00:16:36,656
They always come out
on Fridays round midnight.

166
00:16:36,736 --> 00:16:38,455
They do not. Do they, Mummy?

167
00:16:38,535 --> 00:16:40,975
Yes, you don't see them
cos you're asleep.

168
00:16:41,055 --> 00:16:43,734
Tonight's Friday,
as a matter of fact.

169
00:16:43,814 --> 00:16:47,013
But then you'd be
too bloody bored to see them.

170
00:16:47,093 --> 00:16:50,691
No, I'm not, Mummy.
I promise I won't be bored.

171
00:16:50,771 --> 00:16:54,210
- Even bloody bored?
- Promise!

172
00:16:54,290 --> 00:16:57,729
Well, if you're gonna be up
at midnight, get to bed now.

173
00:17:01,408 --> 00:17:04,687
- Say good night to everybody.
- Good night, everybody.

174
00:17:04,767 --> 00:17:09,965
- Do they really come, Mummy?
- Fairies only live in books.

175
00:17:10,045 --> 00:17:12,884
The Industrial Revolution
killed the fairies.

176
00:17:12,964 --> 00:17:15,363
They were left with nowhere to live.

177
00:17:15,443 --> 00:17:19,642
- Except our imaginations.
- Imaginations are a luxury.

178
00:17:20,602 --> 00:17:23,961
- Beg your pardon?
- Most people can't afford them.

179
00:17:24,041 --> 00:17:27,279
I don't think imagination
is dependent on economics, is it?

180
00:17:27,359 --> 00:17:31,278
In a factory you're doing exactly
the same thing day after day.

181
00:17:31,358 --> 00:17:35,517
An active imagination is what allows
people to do that kind of work.

182
00:17:35,597 --> 00:17:38,236
Oh, well, you'd know, of course!

183
00:17:39,316 --> 00:17:42,914
I just think
that's what you'd have to do.

184
00:17:42,994 --> 00:17:45,673
You'd have to be imagining
other things.

185
00:17:45,753 --> 00:17:48,752
Please don't tell us
what the working class think,

186
00:17:48,832 --> 00:17:50,912
thanks very much.

187
00:18:05,947 --> 00:18:08,266
I think what the Bishop's
really hoping for

188
00:18:08,346 --> 00:18:11,065
is that we can come to a compromise,

189
00:18:11,145 --> 00:18:13,744
find some other examples
of your work.

190
00:18:13,824 --> 00:18:16,143
The great thing is no... Your chair.

191
00:18:16,223 --> 00:18:20,742
- No one wants to see you excluded.
- Now, that is a comfort.

192
00:18:20,822 --> 00:18:24,501
I hadn't realised the Church's
interest in contemporary painting.

193
00:18:24,581 --> 00:18:27,820
It's just The Crucified Venus
we're uncomfortable with.

194
00:18:30,179 --> 00:18:32,698
- Pooh?
- It's me.

195
00:18:32,778 --> 00:18:34,018
Come in.

196
00:18:36,977 --> 00:18:40,695
Poor old Piglet.
Pru gave you a bit of a working over.

197
00:18:40,775 --> 00:18:45,294
I'll survive.
Did you get anywhere with Mr Lindsay?

198
00:18:45,374 --> 00:18:48,613
He insists it's up to the public
to decide for themselves

199
00:18:48,693 --> 00:18:50,252
if they want to see his pictures.

200
00:18:50,332 --> 00:18:53,091
Of course, they have to see them
first to decide,

201
00:18:53,171 --> 00:18:55,651
by which time
the damage has been done,

202
00:18:55,731 --> 00:18:59,329
but that is a bit of logic
which is lost upon him. Never mind.

203
00:19:00,129 --> 00:19:03,248
I'll have another shot
in the morning before we go.

204
00:19:03,328 --> 00:19:06,687
Do you think the pictures
actually damage people?

205
00:19:07,527 --> 00:19:11,006
I think that the sexual ones
are just rather childish

206
00:19:11,085 --> 00:19:13,885
but I do think
negative images build up

207
00:19:13,965 --> 00:19:15,804
and don't any good in the long run

208
00:19:15,884 --> 00:19:20,562
and I think The Crucified Venus
is offensive and downright arrogant.

209
00:19:20,642 --> 00:19:22,562
- I'm coming, I'm coming!

210
00:19:23,401 --> 00:19:26,121
- Hurry up, stupid!
- I'm running as fast as I can,

211
00:19:26,201 --> 00:19:28,360
you disgusting thing!

212
00:19:28,440 --> 00:19:31,999
My guess is they're tooth fairies.

213
00:19:32,079 --> 00:19:34,638
- Shall we?
- Come on, then.

214
00:22:17,225 --> 00:22:19,744
- Swimming?
- What's the time?

215
00:22:19,824 --> 00:22:23,103
The train doesn't leave until 12.

216
00:22:23,183 --> 00:22:24,542
All right.

217
00:22:31,340 --> 00:22:33,299
Anthony.

218
00:22:33,379 --> 00:22:36,378
What'd you do to him?
He's exhausted.

219
00:22:36,458 --> 00:22:39,577
- Anthony!
- Don't wake him up.

220
00:22:39,657 --> 00:22:41,936
Well, he might be dreaming.

221
00:22:42,016 --> 00:22:45,295
It's dangerous to wake somebody up
if they're dreaming

222
00:22:45,375 --> 00:22:48,254
because you leave part
of your brain behind.

223
00:22:48,334 --> 00:22:50,974
If it happens a lot,
you go feeble in the head.

224
00:22:51,053 --> 00:22:54,452
Yeah. You're living proof.

225
00:22:57,291 --> 00:23:00,131
All right, I'll join you in a minute.

226
00:23:23,723 --> 00:23:26,082
- Are you rich?
- Not very.

227
00:23:27,801 --> 00:23:31,480
- What does your father do for crust?
- Why do you ask?

228
00:23:31,560 --> 00:23:35,599
Well, Pru thinks you're bourgeois,
that's all.

229
00:23:35,679 --> 00:23:37,798
Mine was taken by a shark.

230
00:23:37,878 --> 00:23:39,838
God, how awful!

231
00:23:41,157 --> 00:23:42,996
There wasn't much left of him.

232
00:23:43,076 --> 00:23:46,555
So I was brought up mainly by my mum.
She runs a sweet shop.

233
00:23:46,635 --> 00:23:50,794
But I'm quite ambitious all the same.
I was determined to keep my figure,

234
00:23:50,874 --> 00:23:54,673
which was hard with chocolate wombats
and toffee apples everywhere.

235
00:23:54,753 --> 00:23:58,711
- But as you can see, I succeeded.
- Because you wanted to be a model?

236
00:23:58,791 --> 00:24:01,111
Oh, no.
Modelling is just to get known.

237
00:24:01,191 --> 00:24:03,110
